# EKS Best Practices

## Cluster Configuration
- Use private API server endpoint; restrict public access to VPN/bastion CIDRs if enabled
- Enable control plane logging: API server, audit, authenticator
- Use EKS Access Entries (not aws-auth ConfigMap) for IAM-to-RBAC mapping
- Pin EKS add-on versions; upgrade alongside cluster

## Node Management
- Use Karpenter for dynamic scaling with consolidation enabled
- Prefer Graviton (ARM) instances for cost-performance (20-40% savings)
- Use Spot instances for fault-tolerant workloads
- Set appropriate instance types per workload: compute-optimized, memory-optimized
- Enable prefix delegation for high pod density

## Workload Standards
- Set resource `requests` and `limits` on all containers
- Use `topologySpreadConstraints` to distribute pods across AZs
- Configure PodDisruptionBudgets on all production deployments
- Run containers as non-root with read-only root filesystem
- Use dedicated ServiceAccounts with IRSA per workload

## Networking
- Use AWS Load Balancer Controller for ALB/NLB management
- Set target type to `ip` for direct pod routing
- Enable Network Policies (VPC CNI built-in) with default deny
- Use VPC endpoints for ECR, S3, STS, and other AWS services

## Upgrades
- Upgrade one minor version at a time
- Sequence: control plane → managed add-ons → data plane → self-managed add-ons
- Check API deprecations before upgrading
- Test upgrades in non-production first
- Back up cluster state with Velero before upgrade

## Observability
- Deploy Datadog agent (DaemonSet + Cluster Agent) for metrics, logs, traces
- Enable Orchestrator Explorer for Kubernetes resource visibility
- Use unified service tagging (`env`, `service`, `version`) on all workloads
- Alert on node NotReady, pod CrashLoopBackOff, and HPA max replicas
